			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><div class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Actually, it is an ad hominem attack...distracting the discussion by insulting your opponent.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
&gt;&lt;
<br />

<br />
Internet 101 taught you this, but it isn't true.  It is <span style="font-weight: bold">only</span> an ad hominem if the argument is given in the form of X is Y, therefore C. In this case "Rush Limbaugh is a bloated windbag, therefore he is wrong."
<br />

<br />
In this case, him being a bloated windbag and being wrong are simply a coincidence.
<br />

<br />
To reiterate:
<br />

<br />
An insult is not automatically an argumentum ad hominem. It is only an ad hominem when the insult is included as a part of the syllogism in which one "proves" their opponent is false.  Otherwise, it's just an insult.<span class="gensmall"></span>


				</div></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
