				<td colspan="2"><div class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Selph, I have to agree with Poppa that you just totally misssed the boat on this one.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
So people are arguing over the opinion I stated in the last paragraph of my initial post on the topic.  While some may agree that I have "missed the boat on this one", I do see several prominent individuals admonishing Rush for his statements; yet outside of Bill O'Reilly, I see very few people coming to Rush's defense that are noteworthy.  Does that mean my opinion matters more than those who believe otherwise?  No it does not; however, I took a look around the internet just to see what I could find, as I like to believe that I have informed opinions based upon factual evidence.  
<br />

<br />
In my first search, and with little effort, given recent events, I found a couple of comments by Rush in an article that I feel may be relevant to deciding whether or not he would have intended his comments to be derogatory in any way, so I will post them for your reading pleasure.  You can decide for yourself your opinion on Rush:
<br />

<br />
<a href="http://www.bet.com/articles/0,,c1gb7564-8390,00.html" target="_blank" class="postlink">http://www.bet.com/articles/0,,c1gb7564-8390,00.html</a>
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">But this isn’t the first time that Limbaugh -- a former radio and TV talk show host, who was a finalist for the Monday Night Football  analyst job a couple year ago -- has been criticized for acidic remarks against African Americans.  He once told a Black caller to his radio show to “take that bone out of your nose and call me back.” In another instance, he said, “Have you ever noticed how all composite pictures of wanted criminals resemble Jesse Jackson?”</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I know there are other comments by Rush as well that have had racist undertones as well, such as the time he said:
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> "That'd be a double whammy, to get a Democrat plus an African-American in there to take Trent Lott's seat."</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
While some may argue my opinion is mere conjecture, I still believe otherwise and feel that ESPN is better network without Rush Limbaugh.<span class="gensmall"></span>


